          "body": "Joshua 8 opens with a word, not a battle plan. Before a single soldier is repositioned, the LORD speaks: 'Do not fear or be dismayed.' The command is identical in form to the commission of chapter 1 (Joshua 1:9) and to the reassurance given before Jericho. Its repetition here, after the catastrophe of chapter 7, is theologically vital: failure does not disqualify. Sin judged — Achan purged — creates the condition for renewed commission, not permanent disqualification. The LORD does not simply forgive and move on; He re-issues the call with the same authority as the first time. Peter Davids and others in the biblical theology tradition note that this pattern of sin-judgment-renewal is the rhythm of the whole conquest, not an anomaly. The specific content of the commission in verse 2 also matters: Israel may take the plunder and livestock — a deliberate contrast with Jericho where all was devoted (herem). God's commands are not general principles but specific instructions for specific occasions, and obedience requires reading the situation exactly as God defines it rather than applying a previous rule mechanically."
